00:10:13.300 --> 00:10:16.100
We are hardwired for music.

00:10:16.100 --> 00:10:17.710
If I say to you--

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:19.430
and don't be shy right
now, everybody.

00:10:19.430 --> 00:10:21.440
I know you're eating your lunch,
but check this out.

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:25.620
If I say, (SINGING) dun, dun
dun, dun, dun, dun, dun, dun,

00:10:25.620 --> 00:10:26.760
dun, you say--

00:10:26.760 --> 00:10:30.320
AUDIENCE: [SINGING]

00:10:30.320 --> 00:10:34.390
FREDDIE RAVEL: And that
concludes my talk today, and--

00:10:34.390 --> 00:10:35.870
we are hardwired for music.

00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:40.130
We inherently understand
the power of the way

00:10:40.130 --> 00:10:41.900
music is put together.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:47.860
Now music is the great
invitation for mankind to

00:10:47.860 --> 00:10:51.500
transcend spoken word, to
enhance how we think and put

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:56.010
into sync so we hear what
is mostly not heard--

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:02.910
the ground, Mother Earth.

00:11:02.910 --> 00:11:06.810
The holy grail of everything we
do in life revolves around

00:11:06.810 --> 00:11:09.510
the power of listening.

00:11:09.510 --> 00:11:13.650
Nothing can happen unless we are
as present as possible and

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:16.200
we become extraordinary
listeners.

00:11:16.200 --> 00:11:21.040
This is what makes music such
an exceptional, unique, and

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:22.740
powerful tool.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:25.930
Because music is one of the very
few things in life that

00:11:25.930 --> 00:11:28.320
we willingly listen to.

00:11:28.320 --> 00:11:33.095
In fact, we actually
seek it out.

00:11:33.095 --> 00:11:35.530
Remember that saying, we were
given two ears but only one

00:11:35.530 --> 00:11:37.690
mouth because God said
that listening was

00:11:37.690 --> 00:11:40.210
twice as hard as talking?

00:11:40.210 --> 00:11:41.780
Well he--

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:43.280
or she--

00:11:43.280 --> 00:11:45.370
was right.

00:11:45.370 --> 00:11:48.220
I had the great honor and
pleasure to speak over at

00:11:48.220 --> 00:11:51.280
Honda Motors a couple
years ago.

00:11:51.280 --> 00:11:55.640
And I spent some time with the
president, Mr. Tetsuo Iwamura.

00:11:55.640 --> 00:11:57.930
He has the North American
division of Honda.

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:02.270
And he explained to me that
at Honda, the emphasis on

00:12:02.270 --> 00:12:05.470
listening is so powerful, that
it's so critical to their

00:12:05.470 --> 00:12:08.950
success, that "listen" is the
first word in their operating

00:12:08.950 --> 00:12:11.500
principle at Honda Motors.

00:12:11.500 --> 00:12:16.220
And the operating principle at
Honda Motors is "Listen, Ask,

00:12:16.220 --> 00:12:18.020
and Speak Up."

00:12:18.020 --> 00:12:19.380
Now listening takes practice.

00:12:19.380 --> 00:12:21.650
It's a lot of hard work.

00:12:21.650 --> 00:12:23.320
And there's reasons for this.

00:12:23.320 --> 00:12:26.720
You know, we speak at about 150
words a minute, average

00:12:26.720 --> 00:12:27.730
human being.

00:12:27.730 --> 00:12:31.170
But our minds go at 600 to
1,000 words a minute.

00:12:31.170 --> 00:12:33.305
So you say something to
somebody, and their minds have

00:12:33.305 --> 00:12:36.630
raced way ahead of you onto
something entirely different

00:12:36.630 --> 00:12:40.830
like where'd I put my car keys
or should I reply that email.

00:12:40.830 --> 00:12:42.500
People's minds are
wandering right?

00:12:42.500 --> 00:12:44.250
Can everyone relate
to this one?

00:12:44.250 --> 00:12:47.030
You say something to somebody
and they're wandering.

00:12:47.030 --> 00:12:49.540
Very common, right?

00:12:49.540 --> 00:12:50.920
Now there's a reason for this.

00:12:50.920 --> 00:12:54.360
There are basically two
types of listening.

00:12:54.360 --> 00:12:58.250
The first kind of listening is
called passive listening.

00:12:58.250 --> 00:13:01.316
Passive is to listen
without reacting.

00:13:01.316 --> 00:13:02.990
The second one is active.

00:13:02.990 --> 00:13:08.470
Active listening is to
listen for meaning.

00:13:08.470 --> 00:13:09.800
Now I'd like to share with
you a little bit

00:13:09.800 --> 00:13:11.760
about Dr. Peter Senge.

00:13:11.760 --> 00:13:13.470
Dr. Peter Senge is at MIT.

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:18.100
He's been called the business
strategist of the century.

00:13:18.100 --> 00:13:20.680
And Dr. Senge says that to
listen fully means to pay

00:13:20.680 --> 00:13:23.830
close attention to what is being
said beneath the words.

00:13:23.830 --> 00:13:28.590
You listen not only to the music
but also to the essence

00:13:28.590 --> 00:13:31.100
of the person speaking.

00:13:31.100 --> 00:13:33.670
So what turns passive

00:13:33.670 --> 00:13:36.760
listening into active listening?

00:13:36.760 --> 00:13:38.730
Three basic ideas.

00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:40.990
The first one is you've got to
listen for meaning when you're

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:43.120
speaking with anybody and
listening to them.

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:46.670
And number two, you have to
listen for what is being said

00:13:46.670 --> 00:13:48.480
beneath the words.

00:13:48.480 --> 00:13:52.420
And then my favorite is you have
to listen for the space

00:13:52.420 --> 00:13:55.240
between the notes.

00:13:55.240 --> 00:13:56.800
And I've got a little
tune up tip.

00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:59.350
Is it all right if I share with
you a little tune up tip?

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:00.700
Because here it comes.

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:02.800
The tune up tip goes
like this.

00:14:02.800 --> 00:14:04.350
If you take the word
"listen"--

00:14:04.350 --> 00:14:06.170
L-I-S-T-E-N--

00:14:06.170 --> 00:14:08.580
it happens to be an anagram.

00:14:08.580 --> 00:14:10.610
Just by rearranging the letters,
you simply get the

00:14:10.610 --> 00:14:14.970
word "silent." I invite
you all to own this

00:14:14.970 --> 00:14:16.950
one, use this one.

00:14:16.950 --> 00:14:20.350
It will serve you well.

00:14:20.350 --> 00:14:25.940
Now one of the masters of
employing the power of silence

00:14:25.940 --> 00:14:29.420
and the space between the notes
was the great Count

00:14:29.420 --> 00:14:32.170
Basie who we lost about
a decade ago.

00:14:32.170 --> 00:14:38.290
Now Count Basie was considered
the master of swing.

00:14:38.290 --> 00:14:40.260
But he was also a master of the
space between the notes.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:42.392
In fact, he was so good at the
space between the notes that

00:14:42.392 --> 00:14:46.290
he actually developed a riff on
the piano that was filled

00:14:46.290 --> 00:14:47.305
with space between the notes.

00:14:47.305 --> 00:14:48.260
It went like this.

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:52.340
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:14:52.340 --> 00:14:55.520
FREDDIE RAVEL: Audiences fell in
love with this idea so that

00:14:55.520 --> 00:14:58.040
when his big band would play all
over the country, at the

00:14:58.040 --> 00:15:01.190
very end of his songs when he
would play those three notes,

00:15:01.190 --> 00:15:03.300
the entire audience-- and I'm
talking about tens of

00:15:03.300 --> 00:15:07.650
thousands of people-- would say,
(SINGING) Count Basie.

00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:08.990
Filled with space.

00:15:08.990 --> 00:15:11.090
The audience was completely
pulled-in to

00:15:11.090 --> 00:15:12.910
the power of this.

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:14.810
Now the other thing that Count
Basie did is when he would

00:15:14.810 --> 00:15:17.160
play a piece of music,
he'd put a lot of

00:15:17.160 --> 00:15:19.190
space in the notes.

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:20.410
If we take a song--

00:15:20.410 --> 00:15:24.020
a classic American jazz piece
like Duke Ellington's "Satin

00:15:24.020 --> 00:15:26.260
Doll," the song goes
like this.

00:15:26.260 --> 00:15:33.690
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:15:33.690 --> 00:15:35.450
FREDDIE RAVEL: Very famous
jazz tune, right?

00:15:35.450 --> 00:15:36.820
Most pianists--

00:15:36.820 --> 00:15:37.970
many musicians--

00:15:37.970 --> 00:15:40.700
will come to the piano, and
they'll be all about the

00:15:40.700 --> 00:15:43.840
melody, they'll all be about how
many notes can I play and

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:44.670
kind of show off?

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:45.380
What am I going to do?

00:15:45.380 --> 00:15:46.070
And they start playing--

