00:16:06.365 --> 00:16:07.870
FREDDIE RAVEL: Ugh!

00:16:07.870 --> 00:16:10.770
Who wants to hear that?

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:12.540
That's a lot of notes, right?

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:14.482
Do we care?

00:16:14.482 --> 00:16:14.930
No!

00:16:14.930 --> 00:16:16.730
We don't care about that.

00:16:16.730 --> 00:16:21.570
Because when people play too
many notes and when they speak

00:16:21.570 --> 00:16:26.030
to one another and they have
so much to say, there is no

00:16:26.030 --> 00:16:28.870
respect for the listener.

00:16:28.870 --> 00:16:31.660
And Count Basie understood
that you have

00:16:31.660 --> 00:16:33.310
to honor your listener.

00:16:33.310 --> 00:16:36.440
And the space between the
notes invites that.

00:16:36.440 --> 00:16:39.451
So what does Count Basie
do with this song?

00:16:39.451 --> 00:16:42.486
Well he goes like this--

00:16:42.486 --> 00:16:56.558
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:16:56.558 --> 00:16:58.260
FREDDIE RAVEL: You can snap
your fingers if you want,

00:16:58.260 --> 00:16:59.275
right here.

00:16:59.275 --> 00:17:01.532
Give me a little Google
click, right here.

00:17:20.570 --> 00:17:23.530
How's that?

00:17:23.530 --> 00:17:28.050
The space between the notes is
as powerful as the notes

00:17:28.050 --> 00:17:29.470
themselves.

00:17:29.470 --> 00:17:31.990
It is the space between the
bars of a cage that

00:17:31.990 --> 00:17:33.010
keep the tiger in.

00:17:33.010 --> 00:17:34.820
You've got to have that space.

00:17:34.820 --> 00:17:35.650
It's awesome.

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:36.630
It's powerful.

00:17:36.630 --> 00:17:40.260
And it is the structure
of music as the

00:17:40.260 --> 00:17:43.370
structure of success.

00:17:43.370 --> 00:17:48.520
Now I have to tell you, I have
been truly blessed to discover

00:17:48.520 --> 00:17:51.884
many of the tools I'm sharing
with you under the guidance of

00:17:51.884 --> 00:17:53.400
some amazing people.

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.120
I kind of have to pinch
myself sometimes.

00:17:55.120 --> 00:17:57.810
But for many years, I had the
privilege of touring and

00:17:57.810 --> 00:18:01.180
recording with Carlos Santana,
Al Jarreau, Earth, Wind, and

00:18:01.180 --> 00:18:04.060
Fire, Madonna, all these
different artists.

00:18:04.060 --> 00:18:05.670
And I'm very thrilled
to be here.

00:18:05.670 --> 00:18:08.770
Because it's a privilege to
share the tools that I've

00:18:08.770 --> 00:18:12.450
learned from these people and
offer them to you as tools

00:18:12.450 --> 00:18:13.880
that you can use.

00:18:13.880 --> 00:18:16.470
One of these tools is the very
beginning of our first

00:18:16.470 --> 00:18:20.880
foundation, melody.

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:22.130
Melody.

00:18:24.910 --> 00:18:27.470
Melody is the unique signature
of virtually

00:18:27.470 --> 00:18:29.490
every piece of music.

00:18:29.490 --> 00:18:31.040
It shapes the identity.

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:33.420
If you ask anybody how
does that song go?

00:18:33.420 --> 00:18:37.110
People don't go [SINGING].

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:38.450
That's the bass line
of the drums.

00:18:38.450 --> 00:18:40.340
They sing the melody.

00:18:40.340 --> 00:18:42.850
Because the melody is the
identity of the song.

00:18:42.850 --> 00:18:43.810
This is what's critical.

00:18:43.810 --> 00:18:46.900
Now in music, we call
the melody the hook,

00:18:46.900 --> 00:18:48.900
the hook of the song.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:51.090
In business, it's called
the vision.

00:18:51.090 --> 00:18:54.940
And whether it comes from the
lead singer or the CEO of a

00:18:54.940 --> 00:19:00.420
company, it represents the
strength, passion, and purpose

00:19:00.420 --> 00:19:02.950
of the song or the vision.

00:19:02.950 --> 00:19:05.720
And it makes both leaders stand
up and say I am, and

00:19:05.720 --> 00:19:07.420
this is my vision.

00:19:07.420 --> 00:19:11.240
Now our first foundation of
melody is that melody is the

00:19:11.240 --> 00:19:13.520
expression of leadership.

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:15.470
It is the lead idea in music.

00:19:15.470 --> 00:19:17.650
It's the lead idea
in business.

00:19:17.650 --> 00:19:19.850
And leaders, like songs, come
in many different styles.

00:19:19.850 --> 00:19:22.300
You know, some leaders
come in.

00:19:22.300 --> 00:19:24.690
They walk into the room.

00:19:24.690 --> 00:19:25.597
And it's big.

00:19:25.597 --> 00:19:30.652
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:30.652 --> 00:19:31.902
FREDDIE RAVEL: Big!

00:19:36.064 --> 00:19:37.314
Everybody!

00:19:41.476 --> 00:19:43.818
OK!

00:19:43.818 --> 00:19:44.220
Big!

00:19:44.220 --> 00:19:47.390
They come into the room New York
style, Big Apple style,

00:19:47.390 --> 00:19:49.230
kind of Richard Branson style.

00:19:49.230 --> 00:19:51.170
Bigger than life
kind of energy.

00:19:51.170 --> 00:19:54.660
And then you've got executives
that are the opposite.

00:19:54.660 --> 00:19:55.770
They're almost like
quiet power.

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:59.670
You know, the energy's
along these lines.

00:19:59.670 --> 00:20:10.580
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:20:10.580 --> 00:20:12.620
FREDDIE RAVEL: Kind of like
Warren Buffett, you know?

00:20:12.620 --> 00:20:15.040
Quiet power, quiet power.

00:20:15.040 --> 00:20:17.160
And then you've got leaders--

00:20:17.160 --> 00:20:19.310
and this is a trait you will
see in all leaders-- is the

00:20:19.310 --> 00:20:21.700
ability to focus.

00:20:21.700 --> 00:20:25.050
They focus on what they believe
in to such a point

00:20:25.050 --> 00:20:29.570
that if they're dialed in on one
note, irregardless of all

00:20:29.570 --> 00:20:32.950
the distractions, all the
dissonance that comes up, they

00:20:32.950 --> 00:20:35.380
stick to the knitting
of what they believe

00:20:35.380 --> 00:20:37.630
in, along these lines.

00:20:37.630 --> 00:21:39.835
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:21:39.835 --> 00:21:42.076
FREDDIE RAVEL: Can I get
a collective Ole!

00:21:42.076 --> 00:21:43.326
AUDIENCE: Ole!

00:21:45.960 --> 00:21:50.550
FREDDIE RAVEL: No matter how
chaotic the situation is, the

00:21:50.550 --> 00:21:53.770
leaders who focus on that
note irregardless of the

00:21:53.770 --> 00:21:57.700
distractions can punch through
and get their message heard.

00:21:57.700 --> 00:22:00.720
This is what makes leadership
so powerful.

00:22:00.720 --> 00:22:06.140
Now life and business
are team sports.

00:22:06.140 --> 00:22:09.250
And if you ask any leader,
they will tell you that

00:22:09.250 --> 00:22:12.890
they're only as good as the
team that supports them.

00:22:12.890 --> 00:22:15.260
And this brings us, ladies and
gentleman, to our second

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:20.440
foundation of tune up,
which is harmony.

00:22:20.440 --> 00:22:22.790
Harmony.

00:22:22.790 --> 00:22:26.700
Leaders spend a lot of time
listening to their own voices.

00:22:26.700 --> 00:22:28.450
This is kind of where
leaders hang out.

00:22:28.450 --> 00:22:30.260
They hang out on their melody.

00:22:30.260 --> 00:22:33.890
Harmony is the other
side of the coin.

00:22:33.890 --> 00:22:37.000
In harmony, we spend time really
listening to each other

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:39.680
and honoring the spirit
of collaboration.

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:41.870
Harmony is about listening to
one another, but even more,

00:22:41.870 --> 00:22:45.470
harmony is collaboration
with purpose.

00:22:45.470 --> 00:22:50.670
The idea of harmony is making
the shift from "I am" to "we

00:22:50.670 --> 00:22:55.430
are." I am to we are.

00:22:55.430 --> 00:22:57.570
It's almost like in the world
of music going from being a

00:22:57.570 --> 00:23:00.400
solo musician to deciding you're
going to integrate

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:02.660
another member of the band.

00:23:02.660 --> 00:23:04.330
You go from I am to we are.

00:23:04.330 --> 00:23:06.640
You expand the band, right?

00:23:06.640 --> 00:23:08.290
This is very important.

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:12.110
And one of the great tips that
I've enjoyed sharing over the

00:23:12.110 --> 00:23:15.010
years is something I want to
share with Google right now.

00:23:15.010 --> 00:23:20.590
It's called listen to the
question behind the statement.

00:23:20.590 --> 00:23:23.710
Now what's really fun about this
one is that professors of

00:23:23.710 --> 00:23:28.070
music theory often call the
balance in music as the

00:23:28.070 --> 00:23:30.250
question and the answer.

00:23:30.250 --> 00:23:33.130
And good musicians do this
as a matter of practice.

00:23:33.130 --> 00:23:35.310
They know that music is
constructed this way.

00:23:35.310 --> 00:23:39.330
For example, Johann Strauss
writes "The Blue

00:23:39.330 --> 00:23:41.750
Danube." The question--

00:23:41.750 --> 00:23:43.840
[SINGING]

00:23:43.840 --> 00:23:47.090
The answer is--

00:23:47.090 --> 00:23:49.040
don't be shy.

00:23:49.040 --> 00:23:50.190
I'm going to try that again.

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:50.990
The question is--

00:23:50.990 --> 00:23:52.860
[SINGING]

00:23:52.860 --> 00:23:55.100
AUDIENCE: [SINGING]

00:23:55.100 --> 00:23:56.430
FREDDIE RAVEL: Ah, gracias.

