00:24:44.720 --> 00:24:48.750
So this is the power of the
question behind the statement.

00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:52.600
Because once you understand
that, you start to see that

00:24:52.600 --> 00:24:54.250
music is the symmetry.

00:24:54.250 --> 00:24:56.660
All successful music
has a center.

00:24:56.660 --> 00:25:00.150
But what happens when you have
two different viewpoints,

00:25:00.150 --> 00:25:03.010
people getting together--
possibly for the first time--

00:25:03.010 --> 00:25:05.350
and they have two different
questions and

00:25:05.350 --> 00:25:06.680
answers going on?

00:25:06.680 --> 00:25:09.160
So let's say you've got--

00:25:09.160 --> 00:25:12.640
be hypothetical here, let's say
you've got Jane and sales

00:25:12.640 --> 00:25:14.910
and you've got John
in marketing.

00:25:14.910 --> 00:25:17.200
And they both come in with
a lot of enthusiasm.

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:19.710
Jane says hey, I've
got an idea.

00:25:19.710 --> 00:25:23.580
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:25:23.580 --> 00:25:27.060
FREDDIE RAVEL: It sounds
good, right?

00:25:27.060 --> 00:25:29.340
In of its own, it's a very
complete statement, it's full

00:25:29.340 --> 00:25:31.960
of enthusiasm, feels
good, right?

00:25:31.960 --> 00:25:34.200
John walks in and says, hey.

00:25:34.200 --> 00:25:35.110
I've got an idea.

00:25:35.110 --> 00:25:40.060
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:25:40.060 --> 00:25:42.020
FREDDIE RAVEL: In of its own, it
sounds pretty cool, right?

00:25:42.020 --> 00:25:45.970
If you put Jane and John
together and they try to work

00:25:45.970 --> 00:25:49.990
it out, this is what
it sounds like.

00:25:49.990 --> 00:26:01.580
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:26:01.580 --> 00:26:06.050
FREDDIE RAVEL: Happens all
the time on planet Earth.

00:26:06.050 --> 00:26:07.900
What is the fundamental
problem here?

00:26:07.900 --> 00:26:11.320
Well, first of all, neither of
them are really listening to

00:26:11.320 --> 00:26:12.480
one another.

00:26:12.480 --> 00:26:17.940
Number two, they're not
acknowledging each other.

00:26:17.940 --> 00:26:20.660
Because they're in two
completely different keys.

00:26:20.660 --> 00:26:22.150
You put people together.

00:26:22.150 --> 00:26:23.500
They think they've got
the right ideas.

00:26:23.500 --> 00:26:25.270
But their keys are different.

00:26:25.270 --> 00:26:26.400
What has to happen?

00:26:26.400 --> 00:26:27.840
What is the solution?

00:26:27.840 --> 00:26:29.320
Harmony.

00:26:29.320 --> 00:26:32.470
Because the definition of
harmony in Tune Up is

00:26:32.470 --> 00:26:35.320
collaboration with purpose.

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:38.250
Simply by acknowledging each
other, John comes to the

00:26:38.250 --> 00:26:41.510
conclusion that he's only
a half-step off.

00:26:41.510 --> 00:26:42.300
And instead of--

00:26:42.300 --> 00:26:43.685
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:26:43.685 --> 00:26:46.110
FREDDIE RAVEL: --he just needs
to step down a half step,

00:26:46.110 --> 00:26:47.750
readjust his listening.

00:26:47.750 --> 00:26:48.710
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:51.680
FREDDIE RAVEL: And all of a
sudden, we put John and Jane

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:52.740
together, we get--

00:26:52.740 --> 00:27:12.850
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:27:12.850 --> 00:27:15.320
FREDDIE RAVEL: There we go.

00:27:15.320 --> 00:27:17.240
So there you have it.

00:27:17.240 --> 00:27:19.300
John and Jane collaborating
with purpose.

00:27:19.300 --> 00:27:21.640
And this is how we
get from harmony.

00:27:21.640 --> 00:27:27.730
Again, the structure of music
is the structure of success.

00:27:27.730 --> 00:27:32.160
We arrive at our third
foundation, rhythm.

00:27:32.160 --> 00:27:35.515
You can snap along.

00:27:35.515 --> 00:27:36.420
Oh yeah.

00:27:36.420 --> 00:27:41.250
Rhythm, the beat, the timing,
the tempo, rhythm.

00:27:41.250 --> 00:27:45.090
Now we're all going to stop on
beat four, because music that

00:27:45.090 --> 00:27:48.720
has melody and harmony without
rhythm is left with no

00:27:48.720 --> 00:27:49.660
direction whatsoever.

00:27:49.660 --> 00:27:51.120
So we're stopping on four.

00:27:51.120 --> 00:27:57.098
A one, two, a one two,
three, four.

00:27:57.098 --> 00:27:58.348
Space.

00:28:01.310 --> 00:28:08.580
Without rhythm, melody and
harmony drift off into space.

00:28:08.580 --> 00:28:11.810
And as we talk about space, I
need to share a quick story

00:28:11.810 --> 00:28:14.370
with you about NASA.

00:28:14.370 --> 00:28:17.330
About four years ago, I spoke
at the Goddard Space Flight

00:28:17.330 --> 00:28:20.180
Center where they launched
the Hubble telescope

00:28:20.180 --> 00:28:22.690
in Greenbelt, Maryland.

00:28:22.690 --> 00:28:26.280
Now this place has the highest
concentration of

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:27.500
PhD's in the room.

00:28:27.500 --> 00:28:30.840
This is a very melody-heavy
crowd.

00:28:30.840 --> 00:28:35.260
And you have the inventors, the
people that put together

00:28:35.260 --> 00:28:38.260
the Hubble or the Curiosity or
the next missions that are in

00:28:38.260 --> 00:28:39.580
front of us.

00:28:39.580 --> 00:28:42.540
Well these very same
people have harmony

00:28:42.540 --> 00:28:43.157
that supports them.

00:28:43.157 --> 00:28:46.670
You have logistics and human
resources that are providing a

00:28:46.670 --> 00:28:49.400
harmony to those
melody people.

00:28:49.400 --> 00:28:53.010
But the third people that walk
in are the project managers.

00:28:53.010 --> 00:28:56.595
The project managers walk in and
say look, I'm really glad

00:28:56.595 --> 00:28:58.410
that you inventors, you
melody people are

00:28:58.410 --> 00:28:59.510
having a great time.

00:28:59.510 --> 00:29:01.270
I'm thrilled that you
harmony people are

00:29:01.270 --> 00:29:02.890
supporting the melody.

00:29:02.890 --> 00:29:03.510
But you know what?

00:29:03.510 --> 00:29:08.160
If this isn't on my desk by 10
o'clock on Tuesday, that

00:29:08.160 --> 00:29:11.050
proposal that I sent to you,
we're going to pull the

00:29:11.050 --> 00:29:13.980
funding on the entire program.

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:17.930
Now the drummer has shown up.

00:29:17.930 --> 00:29:20.050
Rhythm is in the room.

00:29:20.050 --> 00:29:25.900
Rhythm is the reality check
of where time shows up.

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:30.230
And now we get to our third
foundation, rhythm.

00:29:30.230 --> 00:29:34.120
Rhythm paces action
across time.

00:29:34.120 --> 00:29:36.860
Rhythm paces action
across time.

00:29:36.860 --> 00:29:38.370
And time is money.

00:29:38.370 --> 00:29:40.720
And money is time.

00:29:40.720 --> 00:29:44.220
And time keeps ticking to
rhythm's bottom line.

00:29:44.220 --> 00:29:46.770
And one of the biggest robbers
of time is email.

00:29:46.770 --> 00:29:49.660
We know email's an
incredible tool.

00:29:49.660 --> 00:29:50.430
We all use it.

00:29:50.430 --> 00:29:53.640
There's about 300 billion emails
that are sent around

00:29:53.640 --> 00:29:55.350
the world every 24-hours.

00:29:55.350 --> 00:29:59.440
It comes out to about 2.8
million emails per second that

00:29:59.440 --> 00:30:03.060
are sent around the world.

00:30:03.060 --> 00:30:06.600
What if I told you that the
company that makes the chips

00:30:06.600 --> 00:30:10.640
that most of us have in our
digital devices has a policy

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:12.750
where they ask--

00:30:12.750 --> 00:30:13.950
and highly advise--

00:30:13.950 --> 00:30:18.650
their employees to take email
out of their week, 20% of

00:30:18.650 --> 00:30:20.180
their work week?

00:30:20.180 --> 00:30:22.620
Anybody know who
the company is?

00:30:22.620 --> 00:30:25.220
Let me give you little
musical clue.

00:30:25.220 --> 00:30:27.500
The musical clue is this--

00:30:27.500 --> 00:30:31.780
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:30:31.780 --> 00:30:33.770
FREDDIE RAVEL: Yeah, Intel.

00:30:33.770 --> 00:30:37.210
Intel has a no email
on Fridays rule.

00:30:37.210 --> 00:30:41.350
because they realize that one
day out of the week, it's

00:30:41.350 --> 00:30:45.570
